MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1450768331}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: cd8f8ce2fb929114f841c9e41beb59b6, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ModuleContentController
  moduleImage: {fileID: 1685557932}
  descriptionText: {fileID: 982879396}
  moduleImages:
  - {fileID: -7124896431421053199, guid: 12c03425c5b4c754aa755cc800438e1b, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -1726678742726862053, guid: eeed79dbcf1c9314abff10016ad2c3f1, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -6917630243175427886, guid: 33440cf2527ac7e41915b40a22a21410, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -4231003890421344576, guid: cd70fa8c548883d4989918f8a11481ba, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 7124029903464243350, guid: 7a82846a1517e464ea864639d40e8d04, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 2865387788969864799, guid: eb061faa655e00f4e8c6fc3380a88c5b, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 1848957978638099326, guid: 3e5ecfc380eddf647a72e482a752f54c, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 5146539584360948927, guid: 65f9335930e3f03439e59767a72f7442, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 3917540692578594155, guid: 497567a9fc14c0a448f30ffd39a7255a, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -5516907990497598536, guid: 8f8d0cb7abcce474c9b7310735d3e35f, type: 3}
  descriptions:
  - "A patch panel is a device used in networking to organize and connect multiple
    cables in one place.\r\nThink of it like a power strip\u2014but for internet
    cables.\r\nSimple Idea:\r\nAll cables from different rooms go into the patch
    panel\r\nThen short cables connect the panel to a network device like a switch\r\nExample
    device it connects to:\r\nNetwork Switch\r\n\r\nSimple Analogy\r\nPatch Panel
    = Organizer\r\nCables = Wires from rooms\r\nSwitch = Distributor of internet\r\nSo
    instead of messy cables everywhere, everything is neat and labeled.\r\n"
  - 'Keeps cables organized

    Makes troubleshooting easier

    Cleaner and more
    professional setup

    Used in schools, offices, and computer labs

'
  - 'You will need:

    Patch panel

    Ethernet cables

    Punch-down tool

    Network
    rack or wall mount

'
  - Attach it to a rack or wall securely.
  - 'Bring all Ethernet cables (from rooms/computers) into the panel

    Each cable
    goes into a port at the back

'
  - 'Follow standard color codes:

    T568A

    T568B

    (Your teacher will usually
    tell you which one to use.)

'
  - 'Use a tool like:

    Punch Down Tool

    Push the wires into the correct slots
    to secure them.

'
  - "Write labels like:\r\nRoom 1\r\nLab PC 2\r\n This helps identify connections
    easily."
  - 'Use short Ethernet cables to connect the front of the patch panel to the:

    Network
    Switch

'
  - Check if internet/network is working on all connected devices.
